      <title>Mortals created gods?</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Lore&amp;message.id=12133#M12133</link>
      <description>Don't gods have to get their powers through worship or at least devotion? Even though dark elves, ogres, trolls, elves, paladins, rangers, wizards, iksars and the like all trample through the domains of their gods one thing remains certain. They do so with the ideals that a certain god stands for in their hearts. Paladins still believe in rightousness, ogre warriors in the aspects of war and survival of the fittest, necromancers with the manipulation of the weak and the pursuit of power, rangers and elves in upholding nature or the purity of reality (does that last statement even make sense?) I guess you could say rangers and druids want to uphold a non-shift in power such as mayong or mata muram represent. But then, who dictates what the norm is on norrath? Those who have been in power the longest it can be shown have maniupulated things in such a way it is unnoticeable.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Well if mortals were able to give Mayong his power, that means mortals can't just poof out of thin air to become all/semi powerful and nor can they retain that power regardless of the circumstances. It is apparent through eq lore that there were several races that existed before the main pantheon. Who's to say a god even created them? Vah Shir acknowledge no god. The myriad of races under the control of Mata Muram acknowledge no god. The sarnak were created by the Iksar, yet are more powerful as a race than the Iksar now. They practice wizardry and necromancy both as well as covering more lands in kunark than the iksar. They acknowlege only their potential power.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The Shissar, The ancient race that "created' Bertoxxulus, Erudties (no known divine intervention like Barbarians to Humans took place for the Human to Erudite transformation)&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;These are just 3 among others. If you control the past you control the future, or the perceptions of what everyone thinks. What if dark elves had always been a race, but Innoruuk basicaly wiped out thier history and took control of them? What if the iksar had been around as long as the shissar and Cazic-Thule never created them? How would they know one way or another, they were enslaved up until Sebilis and they are still not doing to well. How is it that Norrath in a way didn't birth the elves and that the idea and zealousness of protecting nature and growth is anchored with that past and formed into the conciousness of Tunare. To say it gave their beliefs a form and since they believe fully enough it is reality.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;But while the gods subtly manipulate they seem to lack the power to directly take a hand in many matters, as in to crush an army in the blink of an eye or a city or some such thing. This has happened a few times. Greenmist, Solusek Ro and the Elddar forest...I can't think of many more, maybe Druzzil Ro and Zeburoxx. Maybe it drains them to interact like this. You would think a seemingly benevolent being like Tunare would want her children to evolve into more powerful beings or even Innoruuk, but no...they just keep them right where they are...feeding? off of the beliefs of these races. They don't seem all powerful in that way. When the gods combine forces they can annhiliate creatues like...the Shissar? I wonder how that's possible.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Didn't in the lore somewhere it said Greenmist was an entity itself? It didn't just serve Fear or Cazic-Thule but was self-aware or something? Maybe all it cares for is destruction but still...the ability to wipe out an entire race isn't something any god has shown himself/herself capable of. Maybe the Greenmist is like a entity weapon that Cazic-Thule keeps imprisoned unless he needs to wipe people out.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Also Solusek Ro seems to have a disgust with the other gods, like he is willing to destroy them and he was the one that bent the mountains and destroyed the elddar. Most gods like I said don't have this type of interactive power. Maybe it is because Solusek represents power itself and it gives him an edge? All beings covet power and in doing so he is innately much more capable than the other gods...does he know this?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Anyway just interesting food for thought in the lore of everquest.&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
